hatred: Strong aversion; intense dislike; hate; an affection of the mind awakened by something regarded as evil
porous: Full of pores; having interstices in the skin or in the substance of the body; having spiracles or passages for fluids; permeable by liquids; as, a porous skin; porous wood
nosed: Having a nose, or such a nose; -- chieflay used in composition; as, pug-nosed
ward: The act of guarding; watch; guard; guardianship; specifically, a guarding during the day
fix: A repair or corrective action. "That plumber's fix is much better than the first one's."
anisic: Of or derived from anise; as, anisic acid; anisic alcohol
merman: The male corresponding to mermaid; a sea man, or man fish
shoer: One who fits shoes to the feet; one who furnishes or puts on shoes; as, a shoer of horses
lurk: To lie hid; to lie in wait
useful: Full of use, advantage, or profit; producing, or having power to produce, good; serviceable for any end or object; helpful toward advancing any purpose; beneficial; profitable; advantageous; as, vessels and instruments useful in a family; books useful for improvement; useful knowledge; useful arts
rice: A well-known cereal grass (Oryza sativa) and its seed
butane: An inflammable gaseous hydrocarbon, C4H10, of the marsh gas, or paraffin, series
faham: The leaves of an orchid (Angraecum fragrans), of the islands of Bourbon and Mauritius, used (in France) as a substitute for Chinese tea
cantar: A weight used in southern Europe and East for heavy articles
burl: To dress or finish up (cloth); to pick knots, burs, loose threads, etc
dromon: In the Middle Ages, a large, fast-sailing galley, or cutter; a large, swift war vessel
tinman: A manufacturer of tin vessels; a dealer in tinware
faith: Belief; the assent of the mind to the truth of what is declared by another, resting solely and implicitly on his authority and veracity; reliance on testimony
allow: To praise; to approve of; hence, to sanction
beckon: To make a significant sign to; hence, to summon, as by a motion of the hand
choric: Of or pertaining to a chorus
bay: Reddish brown; of the color of a chestnut; -- applied to the color of horses
caul: A covering of network for the head, worn by women; also, a net
breton: Of or relating to Brittany, or Bretagne, in France
attle: Rubbish or refuse consisting of broken rock containing little or no ore
mutual: Reciprocally acting or related; reciprocally receiving and giving; reciprocally given and received; reciprocal; interchanged; as, a mutual love, advantage, assistance, aversion, etc
platy: Like a plate; consisting of plates
mantis: Any one of numerous species of voracious orthopterous insects of the genus Mantis, and allied genera
drunk: Intoxicated with, or as with, strong drink; inebriated; drunken; - - never used attributively, but always predicatively; as, the man is drunk (not, a drunk man)
bauble: A trifling piece of finery; a gewgaw; that which is gay and showy without real value; a cheap, showy plaything
aft: Near or towards the stern of a vessel; astern; abaft
punt: To play at basset, baccara, faro
chevet: The extreme end of the chancel or choir; properly the round or polygonal part
buskin: A strong, protecting covering for the foot, coming some distance up the leg
lid: That which covers the opening of a vessel or box, etc
quinic: Pertaining to, derived from, or connected with, quinine and related compounds; specifically, designating a nonnitrogenous acid obtained from cinchona bark, coffee, beans, etc
calced: Wearing shoes; calceated; -- in distintion from discalced or barefooted; as the calced Carmelites
triple: Consisting of three united; multiplied by three; threefold; as, a triple knot; a triple tie
